<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-03-06T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-03-06T04:00:00-05:00" n="916" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d916">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.5034 Business Tax/4: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-03-06T17:00:00+08:00">March 6, 1931—5
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received March 6—9:15 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>107. Legation’s 93, March 1, 3 p.m., paragraph 3.</p>
                        <p>Following from American Consulate at Nanking: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“March 5, 3 p.m. I am informed by the Ministry of Finance that
                                    reports appearing in Chinese press concerning procedure for
                                    collection of business tax are premature. I have been promised
                                    copy of procedure when it is promulgated.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer>For the Minister:<lb/><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Perkins</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>